{
  "answer": "**No specific rule on breaking a fast unknowingly appears in the Āṅgirasa Smṛti.** \n\nThe text defines fasting (*upavāsa*) as abstention from cooked foods along with observance of virtues, devoid of enjoyments.[^1] It prescribes fasting (e.g., for one night) as a penance for ritual impurity from eating followed by contact with a dog or Śūdra, combined with consuming Pañcagavya.[^2] Fasting is also required when a śrāddha rite is obstructed (e.g., by vomiting), with the rite redone the next day.[^3] Various penances involve fasting or barley-water diets, but none address breaking a fast—knowingly or unknowingly.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, ch.1, [p-60c996](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-60c996) (Ang_1.974: \"**The Meaning of Fasting** Abstention from cooked foods, along with the observance of virtues, // Ang_1.974 // is to be known as a fast (*upavāsaḥ* (उपवासः)), devoid of all enjoyments.\").\n\n[^2]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, ch.1, [p-fa0cec](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-fa0cec) (Ang_1.961).\n\n[^3]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, ch.1, [p-8a2d01](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-8a2d01) (Ang_1.948–949).\n\n[^4]: Āṅgirasa Smṛti, ch.1, [full chapter](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/) (multiple penances, e.g., Ang_2.9–12; no mention of breaking a fast).",
